# Proportional-Integral-Derivative Controller | PID

Refs: [wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PID_controller) 

*  Control loop mechanism   
* Uses feedback  
* Used for continuous modulated control   
* Continuously calculates *error value* **e(t)**  
  * e(t) \= setpoint (SP) \- process variable (PV)  
* Applies correction based on   
  * Proportional   
    * Proportional to the current value e(t)   
    * Gain factor K   
  * Integral   
    * Accounts for past value e(t) and integrates over time   
    * Attempt to eleminate the remaining error after the P factor by adding a control efefct due to historic cumalitive value of the errror   
    * Elimination of error stops the growth of I term   
  * Derivative  
    * Best esitmates of the future tren d based on current rate of chagne  
    * Anticipatory control more rapid change yilds greater controlling or dampening effect  
* Automatically applies accurate and responsive correction to a **control function (\*)** 

![][image1]

* Attempts to minimize the error over time by adjustment of control variable u(t) to a new value determined by weighted sum   
* Tunning  
  * Balancing these P, I, D is achieved by loop tunning**(\*)**    
* Control Action   
  *   
* Applicability   
  * Does not guarantee optimal control (\*) of the system or its control stability (\*)  
  * Excessibve delays measurment of the process value is delyaed or the control action does not apply quickly enough   
    * Lead-lag compensations(\*) are erquired   
  * Response of the controller  
    * Responsiveness to an error   
    * The overshoot from a setpoint   
    * Degree of system oscillation   
  * PID controller is broadly applicable since it relies only on the respoonse of the measured process nopt on knowledge or model of the underlying process

Loop Tuning 

* Stability \-\> no unbound o=scillation   
* Can be difficult if multiple conlicting objectives are need to be satisfied  
* When the system involves some non linearity, i.e. some parameters work when the system is at full loa but not at starting up no load condition    
  * Gain scheduling (\*) may be used to switch to different parameters at dfifferent operating region   
* Stability  
  * Unstable output diverges with or without oscillation and is limited only by saturation or mechanical breakage  
  * Instability is caused by excess gain, mostly in the presence of significant lag   
  * Marginal stability (\*)  
  * Laplace Domain (\*)   
    * Total loop transfer function: ![][image4]  
    * K(s) is the PID transfer function(\*)   
    * G(s) is the plant transfer function   
    * Unstable where the closed loop transfer function diverges for some s.   
      * K(s)G(s) \= \-1   
      * | K(s)G(s) | \= 1 with a 180 degree phase shift  
    * Stability is guaranteed when K(s)G(s) \< 1 for frequencies that suffere high phase shifts   
    * Nyquist Stability Criterion (\*)   
* Optimal Behavior   
  * Regulation   
    * Disturvance rejhection \- staying at a given setpoint   
    * Commnad tracking (implementing setpoint changes )   
      * How well the controlled variable tracks the desired value   
      * Rise time and setting time (\*)(\*)   
* Overview of tunning methods   
  * Developing some form of process model and chosing parameters based on dynamic model parameters  
  * Manual tunning can be time consuming when dealing with syustem swith long loop times 

| Method | Advantages | Disadvantages |
| :---: | ----- | ----- |
| [**Manual tuning**](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PID_controller#Manual_tuning) | No math required; online. | Requires experienced personnel |
| [**Ziegler–Nichols**](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PID_controller#Ziegler%E2%80%93Nichols_method) [\[b\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PID_controller#cite_note-22) | Proven method; online. | Process upset, some trial-and-error, very aggressive tuning |
| **Tyreus Luyben** | Proven method; online. | Process upset, some trial-and-error, very aggressive tuning. |
| [**Software tools**](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PID_controller#PID_tuning_software) | Consistent tuning; online or offline \- can employ computer-automated control system design ([*CAutoD*](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CAutoD)) techniques; may include valve and sensor analysis; allows simulation before downloading; can support non-steady-state (NSS) tuning. | Some cost or training involved[\[21\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PID_controller#cite_note-23) |
| [**Cohen–Coon**](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PID_controller#Cohen%E2%80%93Coon_parameters) | Good process models. | Some math; offline; only good for first-order processes |
| [**Åström-Hägglund**](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PID_controller#Relay_\(%C3%85str%C3%B6m%E2%80%93H%C3%A4gglund\)_method) | Can be used for auto tuning; amplitude is minimum so this method has lowest process upset | The process itself is inherently oscillatory |

* Manual tunning   
  * Set Ki and Kd to zero   
  * Increase Kp until the output of the loop oscillates   
  * Kp should be set to approx half of that value for a “quarter amplitude deacay type response (\*)  
  * Increase Ki until any offset is corrected in sufficient time for the process   
	* Increasing too much may cause instability   
  * Increase Kd until the target is reached quickly enough   
	* Too much Kd will cause excessive response and overshoot   
  * While some systems accept overshoot some systems do not   
	* In which case an overdqamped closed-loop system is required which will require a Kp setting significantly less than half that of Kp  setting that was causing oscillation   

| Parameter | Rise time | Overshoot | Settling time | Steady-state error | Stability |
| :---: | ----- | ----- | ----- | ----- | ----- |
| **Kp** | Decrease | Increase | Small change | Decrease | Degrade |
| **Ki** | Decrease | Increase | Increase | Eliminate | Degrade |
| **Kd** | Minor change | Decrease | Decrease | No effect in theory | Improve if Kd small |

* Ziegler-Nichols Method (*)  
  * Ki and Kd are set to zero   
    * Kp is increase until it reaches the ultimate gain Ku   
      * Where the output begins to oscillate   
      * Ku and Tu (the period of oscillation are used to set gains as follows:

| Control Type | Kp | Ki | Kd |
| :---: | :---: | :---: | :---: |
| **P** | 0.05\*Ku | — | — |
| **PI** | 0.45\*Ku | 0.54\*Ku/Tu | — |
| **PID** | 0.60 \* Ku | 1.2 \* Ku / Tu | 3\*Ku\*Tu/40 |

* Cohen-Coon Parameters  
  * Based on first-order \+ time delay model   
  * Tunning parameters were developed to yield a closed-loop response witha decayse ration of ¼  
  * Small change in these parameters may cause close loop system to become unstable   
* Relay (astrom-Hagglund) method  
  * Relay methods temporarily operates the process using bang-bang control	and mesures the resultant osiclations   
  * Output is switched between two values of the control variable   
  * Values must be chose so the process will cross the setpoint   
* Limitations of PID Control   
  * Do not generally provide optimal control   
  * Fundamental difficulty is the PID control is that it is a feedback control system with constant parameters and no direct knowledge of the process  
    * Ovrall performance is reactive and a compromise   
    * Best controller in an observer without a model of the process beteer performance can be obtained by overly modeling the actior orf the process without resorting to an ovserver   
  * When used alone can give poor performance when PID loop gains must be reduced so that the control system does not over shoot, oscillate or hunt about the control setpoint value   
  * Non-linearity may be a problem   
  * To improve pid controllers most signirfically can be done by implementing feed-forward control with knowledge about the system and using PID only to control error   
  * PID can be modified in more minor ways such   
    * gain scheduling   
    * Improving measurements   
      * Higher sampling rate   
      * Precision   
      * Accuracy   
      * Low pass filtering if necessary   
    * Cascading multple PID controllers   
  * Linearity   
    * Linear and particular symmetric   
    * This preformace of PID controllers in non-linear systems is variable   
  * Noise in derivative   
    * Derivative term amplifeis hiegher frequency measurement or process noise that can cause large amounts of change in the output   
    * Often helpful to filter the measurements with low pass filter in order to remove higher-frequency noise components

# Feed forward Control 

Refs: [wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Feed_forward_\(control\)), [BGU](http://www.bgu.ac.il/chem_eng/pages/Courses/oren%20courses/Chapter_9.pdf)

* Pathway within a control system that passes a controlling signal from a source in its eternal engironment to a load in it external environment   
* Feed-forward behavior system responds to its control signal in a pre-defined way without reponding to how the load reacts   
* The control variable adjustment is not error-based   
  * Based on knowledge about the process in the form of a mathematical model of the process and knowledge about or meeasurment of the process disturvbances   
* Combining feedforward with feedback can help to greatly improve the error whenever there is a major disturbance taht can b measured before it affect the process output  
  * At best if the model is perfect the error is reduced to 0 but even without with imprefection the error can be greatly reduced when compared to just using feedback control  
* Feedforward is always used along with feedback because feedback allows to track the setpoint changes and to suppress unmeasured disturbances that are always present in any real process

* ![][image6]  
  * Shows that feedforward does not effect the stability of the system and that can be designed independently
